#: ../auto_examples/linear_model/plot_tweedie_regression_insurance_claims.rst:23
msgid "Tweedie regression on insurance claims"
msgstr ""

#: ../auto_examples/linear_model/plot_tweedie_regression_insurance_claims.rst:25
msgid "This example illustrates the use of Poisson, Gamma and Tweedie regression on the `French Motor Third-Party Liability Claims dataset <https://www.openml.org/d/41214>`_, and is inspired by an R tutorial [1]_."
msgstr ""

#: ../auto_examples/linear_model/plot_tweedie_regression_insurance_claims.rst:29
msgid "In this dataset, each sample corresponds to an insurance policy, i.e. a contract within an insurance company and an individual (policyholder). Available features include driver age, vehicle age, vehicle power, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../auto_examples/linear_model/plot_tweedie_regression_insurance_claims.rst:33
msgid "A few definitions: a *claim* is the request made by a policyholder to the insurer to compensate for a loss covered by the insurance. The *claim amount* is the amount of money that the insurer must pay. The *exposure* is the duration of the insurance coverage of a given policy, in years."
msgstr ""

#: ../auto_examples/linear_model/plot_tweedie_regression_insurance_claims.rst:38
msgid "Here our goal is to predict the expected value, i.e. the mean, of the total claim amount per exposure unit also referred to as the pure premium."
msgstr ""

#: ../auto_examples/linear_model/plot_tweedie_regression_insurance_claims.rst:42
msgid "There are several possibilities to do that, two of which are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../auto_examples/linear_model/plot_tweedie_regression_insurance_claims.rst:44
msgid "Model the number of claims with a Poisson distribution, and the average claim amount per claim, also known as severity, as a Gamma distribution and multiply the predictions of both in order to get the total claim amount."
msgstr ""

#: ../auto_examples/linear_model/plot_tweedie_regression_insurance_claims.rst:48
msgid "Model the total claim amount per exposure directly, typically with a Tweedie distribution of Tweedie power :math:`p \\in (1, 2)`."
msgstr ""

#: ../auto_examples/linear_model/plot_tweedie_regression_insurance_claims.rst:51
msgid "In this example we will illustrate both approaches. We start by defining a few helper functions for loading the data and visualizing results."
msgstr ""

#: ../auto_examples/linear_model/plot_tweedie_regression_insurance_claims.rst:54
msgid "A. Noll, R. Salzmann and M.V. Wuthrich, Case Study: French Motor Third-Party Liability Claims (November 8, 2018). `doi:10.2139/ssrn.3164764 <http://dx.doi.org/10.2139/ssrn.3164764>`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../auto_examples/linear_model/plot_tweedie_regression_insurance_claims.rst:226
msgid "Loading datasets, basic feature extraction and target definitions"
msgstr ""

#: ../auto_examples/linear_model/plot_tweedie_regression_insurance_claims.rst:228
msgid "We construct the freMTPL2 dataset by joining the freMTPL2freq table, containing the number of claims (``ClaimNb``), with the freMTPL2sev table, containing the claim amount (``ClaimAmount``) for the same policy ids (``IDpol``)."
msgstr ""

